commit_message:
Add CLI commands to interact with software-config

This adds the following heat cli commands for interacting
with the config and deployment REST APIs outside of a heat
template.

It adds the following commands:
- config-create
- config-show
- config-delete
- deployment-show
- deployment-metadata
- deployment-delete

This change does not include deployment-create or deployment-update
commands. These will come in a later change once it becomes obvious
how to discover the stack_user_project_id to pass.

Partial-Bug: #1319986
Change-Id: I405560f7bc085cc35d791cd1218691e7999f9502

revisions:
[{'number': 5, 'created': '2015-01-27 18:54:31.000000000', 'files': ['manila/tests/network/neutron/test_neutron_plugin.py', 'manila/network/neutron/api.py', 'manila/tests/share/test_driver.py', 'manila/network/neutron/neutron_network_plugin.py', 'manila/tests/utils.py', 'manila/opts.py'], 'message': "Add Neutron single network plugin

Add two configuration options ('neutron_net_id', 'neutron_subnet_id'), that can

commit_message:
Add Neutron single network plugin

For share drivers that do support handling of share servers may be useful case
when used different share servers but with shared network. This new plugin
allows to use some specific network and subnet from Neutron for all share
servers within some back-end.

Add two configuration options ('neutron_net_id', 'neutron_subnet_id'), that can
be defined as all other opts for network plugins. For each back-end can be
defined it's own pair of these two options if this new plugin is enabled.

New configuration opts accept only IDs and provided subnet should be assigned
to provided network else error will be raised on start of manila-share service.

If provided share-network has values for net and subnet, they will be
redefined.

Implements blueprint neutron-single-network-plugin
Change-Id: Ia803339078dd25e75848c41d3007a166d94fc309

commit_message:
Add filter to image list

* Hides previously broken --page-size option
* Adds --property to image list for filtering on properties
* Adds Visibility, Protected, Owner, Properties/Tags to --long output
* Adds api.utils.simple_filter() for selecting matches out of a list
  of objects
* Adds tests for all of the above
* Updates image docs

There are additional filtering options to be added in later reviews.

Change-Id: I32feff0ad61aae749b33621c817658d7dc90c3aa
Closes-bug: 1401902

commit_message:
Fix identity_uri variable conditional

This fixes a conditional added in
a9f06231830d9a042cb100010bcab0d8479cd759 that was meant to
skip configuration of the deprecated auth parameters only
if both auth_uri and identity_uri have been set.

Previously the identity_uri was missing its $ meaning
the conditional would fail to configure the legacy auth
settings in some cases.

Includes updates to the test cases to catch this condition.

Change-Id: I8ec9b1e064c160d103c5ae847cf79e20c8bca370

commit_message:
pin oslo.messaging to < 1.6.0

because of eventlet incompatibilities stable/* pins eventlet to <
0.16, however because of fixes and features needed in master, the
current requirements definition requires eventlet >= 0.16.1.

This makes oslo.messaging 1.6.0 not able to work with stable/*
projects.

The other alternative would be to make oslo.messaging not specify
eventlet version, and only take it from the projects. However that's a
larger fix to unwind.

... ALSO ...

Pin barbicanclient because it creates a requirements wedge with juno
cinder.

Change-Id: I7a0be6d1b20a6d4220600dd58ff0c0ecc068d0da

commit_message:
Add and use SecurityGroupAgentRpc

Add a new class, SecurityGroupAgentRpc, which is based on
SecurityGroupAgentRpcMixin.  Most uses of SecurityGroupAgentRpcMixin
follow the same pattern, so this class makes it possible to cut
down on some duplicated code.

Make use of SecurityGroupAgentRpc in: linuxbridge, openvswitch, mlnx,
nec, ofagent, oneconvergence, sriovnicagent, bigswitch, and hyperv.

Part of blueprint rpc-docs-and-namespaces.

Change-Id: I2aaa55e8e539e47427e56b4da42321cfcfcde622

With requests-mock 0.5 we can do away with register_uri(method, ..) and
just use the method name as a function. This feels much cleaner and

In the same update there is query string decoding included in the

Change-Id: I43d31576d15b4be72350bebf00733c08a7fb3e6c

commit_message:
Update requests-mock syntax

With requests-mock 0.5 we can do away with register_uri(method, ..) and
just use the method name as a function. This feels much cleaner and
looks more like requests syntax.

In the same update there is query string decoding included in the
history, so we no longer have to manually parse the query strings out of
the url.

Change-Id: I43d31576d15b4be72350bebf00733c08a7fb3e6c

commit_message:
Add power state changing to fake driver's power methods

When nova fake driver tries to power off or power on an instance,
it does not change the powerstate of instance. This code change
adds real power state change in power_off() and power_on()
methods().

Change-Id: I1ac67480569a4787692be86468d4f0a3206dd03b
Closes bug: #1329192

commit_message:
Add abandon script from nova

This adds the abandon_old_reviews.sh from the nova repository into
Neutron. This is handy for cleaning up the neutron review queues
by abandoning stale reviews stuck in the queue with a helpful
message.

commit_message:
Support Modifying Volume Image Metadata

This spec intends to support modifying volume image metadata,
provide Cinder API to allow user to modify an image property
or add new properties.

blueprint support-modify-volume-image-metadata

commit_message:
Force images to disk to avoid corruption

Sometimes images downloaded from glance that are then converted to
raw format end up corrupt.  This is becasue qemu-img uses fiemap to
read blocks from the source image but is not using FIEMAP_FLAG_SYNC,
so blocks and extents that are in the kernel page_cache but not on
disk are skipped.

This results in corrupt images.

Create a new 'workarounds' group and a flag (qemu_force_sync) to force fsync()
This is then used in a helper maybe_fsync() called in fetch_to_raw.

'qemu_force_sync' defaults to True.  It is intended that
distributions that know they have a fixed qemu can add the
appropriate config options to avoid the
fsync() cost.

As mentioned in the code distro status can be tracked at:
    https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Bug1368815

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ieb33489808a71c1fb40cd6835f0bb753dd69e293
Closes-Bug: #1368815
Co-Authored-By: Davanum Srinivas <dims@linux.vnet.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Fix obj_to_dict type filtering

Commit 88f5f2661ee2ba31056251b4cdf91949fca0a031 fixed the python 3
unit tests, but broke obj_to_dict() because client classes were no
longer being filtered out (like nova's ServerManager class). Trying
to remove these by using inspect.isclass() does not work as it does
not recognize these types as classes (perhaps b/c they are being
serialized?). This change reverts to the old style behaviour, but
uses the six class to fix python3 compatibility.

Change-Id: Ief7bba30d983f67cd28d886cd1d3dfd2a45e957d

commit_message:
Fix all py3 related issues

This patch makes output of `tox -epy34` to finish with following message:
>  py34: commands succeeded
>  congratulations :)

Issues:
 * module "__builtin__" was renamed to "builtins" in Python 3

   Related modules:
    - rally.api
    - tests.unit.benchmark.scenarios.vm.test_utils

 * function "map"/"filter" returns "builtins.map"/"builtins.filter" object
   in Python 3 instead of list in Python 2. "builtins.map" and
   "builtins.filter" object is not subscriptable and has no len(), so list
   comprehension is preferable to use and py2/py3 compatible way.

   Related modules:
    - rally.benchmark.context.sahara.sahara_edp
    - rally.benchmark.processing.plot
    - rally.benchmark.sla.base
    - rally.benchmark.types
    - rally.cmd.commands.task
    - rally.cmd.commands.verify
    - tests.unit.benchmark.scenarios.test_base
    - tests.unit.benchmark.wrappers.test_keystone
    - tests.unit.cmd.commands.test_task
    - tests.unit.cmd.commands.test_verify

 * dict.keys()/dict.values() returns "dict_keys"/"dict_values" object in
   Python 3 instead of list in Python 2. so list(dict) and
   list(dict.values()) should be used instead.

   Related modules:
    - rally.benchmark.scenarios.utils
    - rally.benchmark.scenarios.vm.vmtasks
    - tests.unit.cmd.commands.test_show
    - tests.unit.common.test_broker
    - tests.unit.deploy.engines.test_fuel
    - tests.unit.fakes

 * Some changes was made in Python 3 related to data model, so we should
   change our inspect code. See code changes for more details

   Related modules:
    - rally.cmd.cliutils
    - rally.common.utils

 * ConfigParser is more strict for duplicate items in Python 3, so
   duplicates are removed

   Related files:
    - rally/verification/tempest/config.ini

 * Exception object doesn't have "message" attribute in Python 3, so
   if we want to get it, the most proper way is using "getattr"

   Related modules:
    - rally.verification.tempest.config

 * "mock.MagicMock" is not sortable in Python 3, so we should add required
   attributes to fix that.

   Related modules:
    - tests.unit.benchmark.context.test_base

 * assertSequenceEqual assertation method was added in tests.unit.test to
   compare sequence objects

   Related modules:
    - tests.unit.benchmark.context.cleanup.test_resources
    - tests.unit.benchmark.scenarios.nova.test_utils

 * function "range" returns "range" object in Python 3 instead of list
   in Python 2.

   Related modules:
    - tests.unit.benchmark.processing.test_utils

 * keyword arguments should be transmitted to self.assertRaises as kwargs,
   not like a dict

   Related modules:
    - tests.unit.benchmark.scenarios.dummy.test_dummy

Additional changes:
 * Python 2.6 was added to setup.cfg, since Rally supports it.
 * py33, py34 environments were added to tox.ini
 * wrong ignore path was removed from tox.ini
 * made items of bash complition sorted

Several tests are skipped in Python 3 env. For more details see notes in code:
 - tests.unit.benchmark.processing.test_plot.PlotTestCase.test__process_main_time
 - tests.unit.benchmark.processing.test_plot.PlotTestCase.test__process_atomic_time
 - tests.unit.common.test_utils.MethodClassTestCase.test_method_class_for_class_level_method

During porting Rally to Python3, several issues found and fixed in
TempestContext and its unit tests:

 - If process of cleanup is failed, exception is handled and cleanup is
   marked as successfull. This issue was fixed and CleanUpException was
   added to rally.exception module
 - Cleanup was called with wrong path.

Change-Id: If04e873790dcb4c9c882d4be4bf40479deedd36d

commit_message:
Changing publishing mechanism to allow referencing context variables

* All previously published variables can be now access using '$.'
  as in other places. E.g., if we had variable 'var1' in the context
  we can use '$.var1' to access it in 'publish'.
* Action/workflow result can be referenced using "$.taskName.".
  E.g, if task name is 'task0' and its action/workflow returned {x: y}
  then 'x' can be referenced using '$.task0.x' in 'publish'.
* Fixed a lot of unit tests
* Fixed with-items implementation (part related to task output)

Change-Id: Ib7532572dd677b517efd40a812cd3633b5de756f
Closes-Bug: #1412635

subject: Fix multipolicy simulation bug
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2015-01-27 21:45:39.000000000', 'files': ['congress/policy/compile.py', 'congress/tests/policy/test_runtime.py', 'congress/policy/base.py', 'congress/policy/materialized.py', 'congress/policy/topdown.py', 'congress/policy/unify.py', 'congress/policy/database.py', 'congress/policy/nonrecursive.py'], 'message': 'Fix multipolicy simulation bug

Previously, there was a bug in the simulation functionality when
using action descriptions.  The simulation functionality simply failed
to compute the proper updates given an action instance, thereby the results
of simulation were wrong.

This bug fix does a number of things
1) Only allows policies to appear in the tablenames in the head of a rule
within an ActionTheory if that tablename is an update (i.e. has a + or -
at the end of the tablename).

2) Changes the policy evaluation algorithms to treat an update literal
as a local table even if the literal references a separate policy.

3) Changes the implementation of simulation (the consequences
routine in particular) so that it would generate the appropriate
queries for computing proper updates caused by an action instance.

4) Changes the routine for get_arity to take a theory as an argument
and enable a local_only option so that we compute the arity from
the proper policy in the case of updates.

Change-Id: I27564891e0ea4cc463127f1811edd275c27d568f
Closes-bug: 1413793
'}]
commit_message:
Fix multipolicy simulation bug

Previously, there was a bug in the simulation functionality when
using action descriptions.  The simulation functionality simply failed
to compute the proper updates given an action instance, thereby the results
of simulation were wrong.

This bug fix does a number of things
1) Only allows policies to appear in the tablenames in the head of a rule
within an ActionTheory if that tablename is an update (i.e. has a + or -
at the end of the tablename).

2) Changes the policy evaluation algorithms to treat an update literal
as a local table even if the literal references a separate policy.

3) Changes the implementation of simulation (the consequences
routine in particular) so that it would generate the appropriate
queries for computing proper updates caused by an action instance.

4) Changes the routine for get_arity to take a theory as an argument
and enable a local_only option so that we compute the arity from
the proper policy in the case of updates.

Change-Id: I27564891e0ea4cc463127f1811edd275c27d568f
Closes-bug: 1413793

commit_message:
Cache schema generation

Previously each time one called get_schema() on a datasource_driver we would
generate it by walking through all of the translators. This patch changes the
logic so that we store the schema when we register a datasource so we do not
have to generate it each time. Note: the schema never changes durring run time
so we're able to cache it like this.

Change-Id: I4deead9fa698e681c0f0a8f07a4ef7d95726bae7
Closes-bug: #1415208

subject: Auto add a cinder lvm.conf file
revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2015-01-22 19:28:22.000000000', 'files': ['lib/cinder_backends/lvm', 'lib/cinder'], 'message': "Auto add a cinder lvm.conf file

We have a number of issues where LVM scan commands hang during
test runs.  Looking closer at this with strace it turns out
that what seems to be happening is that we're scanning all of the
devices on the node, this includes the loop devices for swift and
other projects as well as the Cinder devices that are being attached
to the system during the test.

This is particularly messy for example when we issue a VG or LV scan
on a device like /dev/vdb and at the same time issue a detach.  The
result is LVM scan commands hanging waiting for timeout.

This patch adds a function to the cinder_backend/lvm module which
is called as the last part of cinder init.  If Cinder LVM is in use
as per cinder.conf this function will copy the default
/etc/lvm/lvm.conf to /etc/cinder/lvm.conf and use the cinder.conf file
and PVS to create filters so that ONLY the devices actually being used
by Cinder are included in scans.

There are two pieces to this fix; the first is to properly setup an
lvm.conf file with filters.  The second step is to merge the Cinder
change that modifies the Cinder LVM commands to specify the lvm.conf
file usage.

The Cinder part of this fix can be found here:
    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/148747/

Change-Id: I962b6e21cbfb6f5612b6c973053d86828ca8071a
Partial-Bug: #1373513
"}]
commit_message:
Auto add a cinder lvm.conf file

We have a number of issues where LVM scan commands hang during
test runs.  Looking closer at this with strace it turns out
that what seems to be happening is that we're scanning all of the
devices on the node, this includes the loop devices for swift and
other projects as well as the Cinder devices that are being attached
to the system during the test.

This is particularly messy for example when we issue a VG or LV scan
on a device like /dev/vdb and at the same time issue a detach.  The
result is LVM scan commands hanging waiting for timeout.

This patch adds a function to the cinder_backend/lvm module which
is called as the last part of cinder init.  If Cinder LVM is in use
as per cinder.conf this function will copy the default
/etc/lvm/lvm.conf to /etc/cinder/lvm.conf and use the cinder.conf file
and PVS to create filters so that ONLY the devices actually being used
by Cinder are included in scans.

There are two pieces to this fix; the first is to properly setup an
lvm.conf file with filters.  The second step is to merge the Cinder
change that modifies the Cinder LVM commands to specify the lvm.conf
file usage.

The Cinder part of this fix can be found here:
    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/148747/

Change-Id: I962b6e21cbfb6f5612b6c973053d86828ca8071a
Partial-Bug: #1373513

commit_message:
Fix AttributeError during startup of ovs agent in DVR mode

Make sure the agent starts processing incoming requests only after the entire
initialization is complete. This is done by making explicit when the rpc loop
is supposed to start, i.e. right at the end of the init process.

This fix was necessary because the agent starts processing rpc messages even
though it has not completed the entire initialization of bridges and data
structures; this is usually okay, but in case of DVR, this leads to a
situation where during the the first run, the agent asks the server to be
assigned a MAC address; this in turn leads the server to fanout the generated
MAC to the running agents, the requesting one included; because of the
incomplete setup, the above mentioned error occurs. During subsequent
restarts, the problem no longer appears.

Closes-bug: #1395196

Conflicts:
	neutron/plugins/openvswitch/agent/ovs_neutron_agent.py
(cherry picked from commit aa728c00bab3bb6b3e00866e44ca054b1e848bb6)
Change-Id: I792697b94fef39971693cf8aff715c270601cecb

commit_message:
Fix setting Primary Project for new user once the project was created

When the project is being created via pressing '+' button at Create
User form, it is important to store the reference to it inside the
`workflow.object` attribute, otherwise [None, None] value will be
returned to the client-side code which will cause appending "null"
value to the list of available projects - instead of adding the newly
created project name and selecting it as the current value.

Change-Id: I10fcb1f2fb51e341b15901d4f014f0e4faca3adf
Closes-Bug: #1410129

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V boot from volume live migration

Live migration fails on Hyper-V when boot from volume is used with
CoW, as the target host tries to cache the root disk image in
pre_live_migration, but in this case the image_ref is empty.

This patch adds a check to handle the empty image_ref case.

Note(claudiub): test_livemigrationops.py change (1 line) was not
included, since the file did not exist in Juno.

Co-Authored-By: Claudiu Belu <cbelu@cloudbasesolutions.com>
Co-Authored-By: Adelina Tuvenie <atuvenie@cloudbasesolutions.com>

(cherry picked from commit d3758b6532f36f24862d05a761878599d4160974)

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/unit/virt/hyperv/test_livemigrationops.py

Change-Id: I60cb60ccaeb0cb8c536906d897249e31ae396923
Closes-Bug: #1362075

When creating a volume from a glance image, cinder stores the original
image metadata in volume_glance_metadata. This is a key/value store,
and all the values are strings.

When Nova boots an instance from a volume, it passes the image
metadata returned by cinder, which is all strings. If a driver
expects these values to be ints, as they are when booting from an
image, it will get a type error.

This change also pulls size from the volume directly rather than
taking the value from the stored image metadata. This is because the
volume will have been created in 1Gb increments, and is unlikely to be
the same size as the original image. It may also have been
subsequently extended.

Cherry picked from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/124010/

Closes-Bug: #1367540

Conflicts:
	nova/compute/api.py
	nova/tests/compute/test_compute.py

Change-Id: I7928f6be1ca99f1502941b9df2b443f2ca63a37b

commit_message:
Fix image metadata returned for volumes

When creating a volume from a glance image, cinder stores the original
image metadata in volume_glance_metadata. This is a key/value store,
and all the values are strings.

When Nova boots an instance from a volume, it passes the image
metadata returned by cinder, which is all strings. If a driver
expects these values to be ints, as they are when booting from an
image, it will get a type error.

This change also pulls size from the volume directly rather than
taking the value from the stored image metadata. This is because the
volume will have been created in 1Gb increments, and is unlikely to be
the same size as the original image. It may also have been
subsequently extended.

Cherry picked from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/124010/

Closes-Bug: #1367540

Conflicts:
	nova/compute/api.py
	nova/tests/compute/test_compute.py

Change-Id: I7928f6be1ca99f1502941b9df2b443f2ca63a37b

subject: Exclude empty tiers from max_replicas
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 330, 'name': 'John Dickinson', 'email': 'me@not.mn', 'username': 'notmyname'}, {'_account_id': 1179, 'name': 'Clay Gerrard', 'email': 'clay.gerrard@gmail.com', 'username': 'clay-gerrard'}, {'_account_id': 2622, 'name': 'Samuel Merritt', 'email': 'sam@swiftstack.com', 'username': 'torgomatic'}, {'_account_id': 7233, 'name': 'Matthew Oliver', 'email': 'matt@oliver.net.au', 'username': 'mattoliverau'}, {'_account_id': 13052, 'name': 'SwiftStack Cluster CI', 'email': 'openstack-ci@swiftstack.com', 'username': 'swiftstack-cluster-ci', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}]
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2015-01-16 22:49:36.000000000', 'files': ['swift/common/ring/builder.py', 'test/unit/common/ring/test_builder.py'], 'message': "Exclude empty tiers from max_replicas

If you have ring with less failure domains at a tier than replicas the
max_replicas count for the failure domains at that tier already expect to have
a max_replicas > 1.  For example, on a two node deployment, each of the two
failure domains at the server tier is expected to have no more than *two*
replicas of any part (surely it would be a problem if either server had all
three replicas, but we expect some doubling).  If you have a third server, the
max_replicas drops from 2 to 1 at each of those failure domains as they should
only have at most a single copy of any partition or there's a dispersion
problem.

But if that third server is being decommissioned and all of it's device's
weight are set to zero then you don't really have three failure domains at
that tier and the max_replicas should be go back to 2 not 1.  Also any parts
stuck in the tier with weight zero probably shouldn't be there - so you've got
some kind of problem if there's *any* replicas in a zero weight tier
*regardless* of the number of failure domains.

I came to this when I was playing around with a topology migration that was
moving a zone.  You start with two zones and everything is dispersed, you add
a third zone and everything gets even *more* dispersed, then you remove one of
the first zones that you're migrating off of and suddenly there's a problem
because the two zones you're migrating to have > 1 replica of some parts.  Two
zones was fine before, so what's the problem?

Turns out the problem was a failure domain with zero weight still drains off a
replica from the max_replicas of the other failure domains at that tier.

Eventually I think it's pretty sane that the operator would remove the zero
weight devices from the ring, and then max_replicas will go back to saying
each of the two failure domains at this tier may have at most 2 replicas.  But
because it's not always obvious when replication is finished just by looking
at partition placement theres a disconnect and window where things seem to be
saying it's worse than it really is.

When a tier has zero weight max_replicas acts like the max_replicas at that
tier should be 0.  We do expect that occasionally a tier with zero weight will
have replicas assigned to it because min_part_hours - but I think thats also
bad and worth flagging as a dispersion problem - although maybe it's
conflating of seperate issues.

Someone else might have a counter example where this would not be the desired
behavior, and I'm not 100% sure it's going to always say the right thing in
every use case - but as it's done currently I've got at least one concrete
example where I think the current behavior doesn't make sense.

Change-Id: I68d47ff0667788442342d55b8041aed80d0b2161
"}]
commit_message:
Exclude empty tiers from max_replicas

If you have ring with less failure domains at a tier than replicas the
max_replicas count for the failure domains at that tier already expect to have
a max_replicas > 1.  For example, on a two node deployment, each of the two
failure domains at the server tier is expected to have no more than *two*
replicas of any part (surely it would be a problem if either server had all
three replicas, but we expect some doubling).  If you have a third server, the
max_replicas drops from 2 to 1 at each of those failure domains as they should
only have at most a single copy of any partition or there's a dispersion
problem.

But if that third server is being decommissioned and all of it's device's
weight are set to zero then you don't really have three failure domains at
that tier and the max_replicas should be go back to 2 not 1.  Also any parts
stuck in the tier with weight zero probably shouldn't be there - so you've got
some kind of problem if there's *any* replicas in a zero weight tier
*regardless* of the number of failure domains.

I came to this when I was playing around with a topology migration that was
moving a zone.  You start with two zones and everything is dispersed, you add
a third zone and everything gets even *more* dispersed, then you remove one of
the first zones that you're migrating off of and suddenly there's a problem
because the two zones you're migrating to have > 1 replica of some parts.  Two
zones was fine before, so what's the problem?

Turns out the problem was a failure domain with zero weight still drains off a
replica from the max_replicas of the other failure domains at that tier.

Eventually I think it's pretty sane that the operator would remove the zero
weight devices from the ring, and then max_replicas will go back to saying
each of the two failure domains at this tier may have at most 2 replicas.  But
because it's not always obvious when replication is finished just by looking
at partition placement theres a disconnect and window where things seem to be
saying it's worse than it really is.

When a tier has zero weight max_replicas acts like the max_replicas at that
tier should be 0.  We do expect that occasionally a tier with zero weight will
have replicas assigned to it because min_part_hours - but I think thats also
bad and worth flagging as a dispersion problem - although maybe it's
conflating of seperate issues.

Someone else might have a counter example where this would not be the desired
behavior, and I'm not 100% sure it's going to always say the right thing in
every use case - but as it's done currently I've got at least one concrete
example where I think the current behavior doesn't make sense.

Change-Id: I68d47ff0667788442342d55b8041aed80d0b2161

subject: Move self.rules implementations to TopDownTheory subclasses
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-01-23 18:51:14.000000000', 'files': ['congress/policy/topdown.py', 'congress/policy/nonrecursive.py'], 'message': "Move self.rules implementations to TopDownTheory subclasses

Previously, TopDownTheory assumed that it's subclasses would define a field
called self.rules.  This change eliminates that assumption by moving any code
that uses self.rules to the subclass NonrecursiveRuleTheory.

This new organization makes it cleaner for a subclass of TopDownTheory to
implement self.rules in a different way because now TopDownTheory will not be
reaching into self.rules at all.  Instead, methods like head_index(), head(),

Change-Id: Id0c2ff09a11ca37dfafda6efda951d503d2b05b9
"}]
commit_message:
Move self.rules implementations to TopDownTheory subclasses

Previously, TopDownTheory assumed that it's subclasses would define a field
called self.rules.  This change eliminates that assumption by moving any code
that uses self.rules to the subclass NonrecursiveRuleTheory.

This new organization makes it cleaner for a subclass of TopDownTheory to
implement self.rules in a different way because now TopDownTheory will not be
reaching into self.rules at all.  Instead, methods like head_index(), head(),
and body() are all implemented in the subclass.

Change-Id: Id0c2ff09a11ca37dfafda6efda951d503d2b05b9

commit_message:
Use __slots__ for runtime classes

This change saves memory by using __slots__ instead of allocating a dict for
every instance of Location, Variable, Literal, Rule, and Event.  The overhead
of a dict is significant when there are many object instances using a dict to
store internal state.

Change-Id: I0f4f01e42f1641d624ab76ac304ad037767d0d9f

commit_message:
Provide Rackspace service_name override

Rackspace puts two compute services in their catalog. This means that
keystone session code cannot find the right one without a name match
override.

Change-Id: I1bc06b97261341ad01bf84ebf5a12294cd0d383c

commit_message:
Refactor metering utility and view functions

Many of these functions have been copied to Tuskar-UI and then have
diverged in both places. This is an attempt to consolidate these
functions and eliminate any code duplication. These modifications
to horizon utility and view metering functions should make it possible
to delete the duplicated code from Tuskar-UI.

Change-Id: Ie73b350303a3e42229d87dbbfccf7ecff859cbd7

commit_message:
removing mandatory mark for post_creation tab

In launch instance form the post creation tab
having the * symbol, which means the the script
data is mandatory. but this is optional field.

so removing the the * symbol from the
post-creation tab.

(cherry picked from commit db33f9f944eed44171bbe744c88d8985275af26b)

Conflicts:
	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/instances/workflows/create_instance.py

commit_message:
ephemeral file names should reflect fs type and mkfs command

At some point, we should switch over from ext3 to ext4. If we have
'default', we can't tell if a file was created with ext3 or ext4
as the file system. So we need a better way.

The name format is from discussion on the mailing list [1] and
was proposed by P√°draig Brady. Once we have this in place, we
can resurrect changeset to switch over from ext3 to ext4
first proposed by lifeless in
I833356af81df743a63d4442d389be82bc25f3914 and reverted in
I8de225729bbc77b263fcac2fa72b0e9cc6c1b2bf.

[1] http://markmail.org/message/xzwt2r7acyj7n33t

Related-Bug: #1266262
Change-Id: I795d4165d668018658967661f593a9eb48652b2b

commit_message:
Only enable one images filter button

Only one button for the images filter buttons should be enabled at any one time.
This is solved by removing the active class from all the filter buttons upon
selecting a filter.

(cherry picked from commit 8ea177b67a28b328b571b1140b7db01e303f6abc)

Closes-bug: 1365803
Change-Id: I9d7753684f144a6d66ccc5b09f830b360a07a620

commit_message:
Deprecate compute_node_get_by_service_id in DB API

As this method is only in use in the ComputeNode object, we can deprecate it
on the DB API layer and provide backwards compatibility within the object.

To be clear, we're now claiming that accessing the DB compute_nodes table
using a service_id field is no longer wanted and will be removed in
a next future once we are sure that all compute nodes are having an host field
set (ie. once all nodes in production are running Kilo code because we added
this field in a previous patch)

Partially-Implements blueprint detach-service-from-computenode

Change-Id: Icaa87ea803bc8d217eaece9bfa6a993af89fd460

commit_message:
Adds a dynamic subheading to delimit floating IPs

When an instance has floating IP addresses associated to it, a new
subheading appears in the IP Address column in the instances table to
provide the user with a easy way to see which IPs are fixed and
which are floating.

Closes-Bug: 1284175

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Fixes wrong hypervisor_version

The hypervisor_version will be stored in the database as
an Integer and it will be used by the scheduler, if required
by the image property 'hypervisor_version_requires'.

The hypervisor_version will then be converted back to a version
by spliting the int in groups of 3 digits.
E.g.: hypervisor_version 6003 is converted to '6.3'.

Currently, the reported hypervisor_version by the Hyper-V driver
is wrong. For example, for Windows Hyper-V / Server 2012 R2
or Windows 8.1, the hypervisor_version reported is '639600',
which will later be converted to 639.600 by the scheduler.

Closes-Bug: #1409258

Change-Id: Id991fefed08d1da2a68db4c27de72ac2252b1781

The standard flow in the SolidFire volume is to create

Unfortunately the clone_image method "forgot" about this

commit_message:
Create SolidFire Template account on init

The standard flow in the SolidFire volume is to create
accounts dynamically as needed based on project id.
Unfortunately the clone_image method "forgot" about this
detail and calls the private clone_volume method without
a valid account resulting in an AccountNotFound
Exception.

The clone_image method is enabled using a specific account
provided via the configuration file.  Rather than worry
about dynamic account creation on clone_image call, this
patch just makes it part of the init phase.  We check to
see if template caching is enabled and if it is, just
go ahead and check/create the account on startup.

Closes-Bug: #1414760

Change-Id: I62f3f7aff958c097ae662d21b2c0f55a8d08f784

subject: mirror/docker: fix the cleanup rule
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-01-27 15:44:06.000000000', 'files': ['mirror/docker/module.mk'], 'message': 'mirror/docker: fix the cleanup rule

After the commit 59b10c0d543af17eb88af43360df0f31337db68b ("Refactor Docker
cleanup") no docker containers/images get actually removed, so building ISO
exhausts the disk space quite quickly. To fix the problem
- Properly quote the special characters so awk command is valid
- Use xargs -r instead of reinventing it

Change-Id: Ie35906edde2fc04d5c3adef0578d1efb4e9a9d64
'}]
commit_message:
mirror/docker: fix the cleanup rule

After the commit 59b10c0d543af17eb88af43360df0f31337db68b ("Refactor Docker
cleanup") no docker containers/images get actually removed, so building ISO
exhausts the disk space quite quickly. To fix the problem
- Properly quote the special characters so awk command is valid
- Use xargs -r instead of reinventing it

Change-Id: Ie35906edde2fc04d5c3adef0578d1efb4e9a9d64

subject: tests: fix relative test failing sometimes
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-01-27 17:27:10.000000000', 'files': ['gnocchi/tests/test_rest.py'], 'message': 'tests: fix relative test failing sometimes

Since no timestamp was force in set_time_override(), now() was used by
default. The problem is that since we query on the last 10 minutes, if
now().minutes is <= 10, we might end up with the hourly aggregation
being returned so the assertEquals fail for a good reason.

Change-Id: Ia1b902440c5fc062ab2c944127e31a7dd7588d66
'}]
commit_message:
tests: fix relative test failing sometimes

Since no timestamp was force in set_time_override(), now() was used by
default. The problem is that since we query on the last 10 minutes, if
now().minutes is <= 10, we might end up with the hourly aggregation
being returned so the assertEquals fail for a good reason.

Change-Id: Ia1b902440c5fc062ab2c944127e31a7dd7588d66

commit_message:
Update the VMTask class with a boot_ping method

with a default of using floating_ip
allocation.  Alternatively depending on the
tenant network type, and if the rally host
has direct access to VLAN on which VMs are
being generated, private_network IP may
be suitable for ping testing.

subject: Partially revert database tests patches.
revisions:
[{'number': 6, 'created': '2015-01-27 16:18:03.000000000', 'files': ['gnocchi/gendoc.py', 'gnocchi/tests/base.py', 'requirements.txt', 'setup-mysql-tests.sh', 'setup-postgresql-tests.sh'], 'message': 'Partially revert database tests patches.

This partially reverts commit 01fb4f0af450a07619c26a72011c9a564b8b0bd7
and 5b9b43b88015348ef6816eba73283f7e5a1cc2fb

The first commit slowed down the test by a factor of 4, which turns out
be too much to my taste.
The second one is buggy as it tries to use a directory for locking that
is unique to a process, but since we run tests in parrallel, we need a
unique directory for ALL the process, so it has to be passed down as a
env variable.

Change-Id: I3fcccef0915eace1b23297d38d1a0a4212a13ff3
'}]
commit_message:
Partially revert database tests patches.

This partially reverts commit 01fb4f0af450a07619c26a72011c9a564b8b0bd7
and 5b9b43b88015348ef6816eba73283f7e5a1cc2fb

The first commit slowed down the test by a factor of 4, which turns out
be too much to my taste.
The second one is buggy as it tries to use a directory for locking that
is unique to a process, but since we run tests in parrallel, we need a
unique directory for ALL the process, so it has to be passed down as a
env variable.

commit_message:
Switch to oslo.vmware API for reading and writing files

This started off as an exercise to remove httplib.HTTPSConnection
to prevent MiM attacks but morphed into a full fledged replacement
of code in read_write_util to use functionality from oslo.vmware.

As a side-effect, we remove the use of the HTTPSConnection and
are switching over to requests library as well.

Closes-Bug: #1374000
Change-Id: I917c34042c501af03725b0504542e00e7d80e511

commit_message:
Ignore warnings from contextlib.nested

We have a lot of warnings in py27 jobs about the
with statements that use contextlib.nested()
construct. We should just ignore them for now.

Alternatives tried included
- multiple manager form of the with statement which essentially
needed to be line wrapped with \ and would have caused a lot of
code changes.
- custom implementation of nested() turned out to be
more complicated than initially thought.

Change-Id: I1b8ed531be91faeb0067aad7338bd8868d16e50d

version made this particular mode to fail to assign addresses to

commit_message:
dhcp: move dnsmasq version check to sanity_check

We should avoid checking version numbers in runtime. In that way, we may
break some existing setups by minimal version bumps that are often not
critical for operation. One example is a recent version bump to support
IPv6 DHCP stateful address assignment mode. Even though old dnsmasq
version made this particular mode to fail to assign addresses to
instances, other IPv6 modes, and, even more importantly, all IPv4
networks continued to operate with no issues.

So let's move the fatal check from DHCP agent into sanity_check tool to
avoid potential breakages on neutron update.

In ideal world, we would make the check smarter. Since current version
cap is due to missing hwaddr matching for IPv6 clients for old dnsmasq
versions, we could preconfigure and start up dnsmasq server in a
namespace, and request a IPv6 lease from it. That would require a DHCP
IPv6 client installed though, and I'm not sure we can always expect it
to be present, so leaving it as-is for now.

Since DHCP drivers are pluggable, we cannot drop check_version method
from DhcpBase to support other drivers that may live in the wild.

Note: we could mark the method as deprecated if we really want to get
rid of it.

Closes-Bug: #1412818
Change-Id: I7a75cccf3880d3b18005ae0def5a17dfd8a00182

SSH private key or user password is not passed during object creation.
The create () method does not allow private key to be discovered in
the default ~/.ssh folder when trying to authenticate or connect
to the SSH server. Instead allow auto discovery of the key in the
paramiko SSHClient's connect method (called in create () method) if the
path to private key or password is not provided.

Also make the following minor cleanups in the

create() method of SSHPool class:
- pass the path to the key file input directly to the SSHClient's
  connect () method using the appropriate parameter, keyfile, instead
  of picking key from key file and passing that as 'pkey' parameter.
- restrict the try except block to only the steps involved in
  connecting to the SSH server.
- reraise the exception that would be raised by the Paramiko library
  instead of raising own exception.

initialization method of SSHPool class:
- rename the attribute privatekey as path_to_private_key to accurately
  reflect what it refers to, the path of the private key file.

Change-Id: I590702d97086d33245894fd686250e75e8e359f2
Closes-Bug: #1412782
"}]
commit_message:
utils: Allow discovery of private key in ~/.ssh

A SSHPool class object, used to hold ssh connections, fails to
authenticate to the server in its create () method if the path to
SSH private key or user password is not passed during object creation.
The create () method does not allow private key to be discovered in
the default ~/.ssh folder when trying to authenticate or connect
to the SSH server. Instead allow auto discovery of the key in the
paramiko SSHClient's connect method (called in create () method) if the
path to private key or password is not provided.

Also make the following minor cleanups in the

create() method of SSHPool class:
- pass the path to the key file input directly to the SSHClient's
  connect () method using the appropriate parameter, keyfile, instead
  of picking key from key file and passing that as 'pkey' parameter.
- restrict the try except block to only the steps involved in
  connecting to the SSH server.
- reraise the exception that would be raised by the Paramiko library
  instead of raising own exception.

initialization method of SSHPool class:
- rename the attribute privatekey as path_to_private_key to accurately
  reflect what it refers to, the path of the private key file.

Change-Id: I590702d97086d33245894fd686250e75e8e359f2
Closes-Bug: #1412782

commit_message:
Fixes Error message during image upload due to file filtering

When filtering supported file types in Glance, uploading a none supported
file gives a none informative/misleading error on Horizon -> Error:
Unable to create new image.
Uploading same image in Glance CLI returns a better warning: Invalid
disk format.

Change-Id: I3dced3a1056bd5bb4495881f246fcab39fbc1bff
Closes-bug: #1296722

commit_message:
Fix disappearing Sahara workflow navbar in 'Jobs' panel

The jquery selector used before in Sahara-specific js was too wide so
it could seize even the modal workflows from the depth of modal stack
(i.e. currently hidden workflows) - which lead to damaging these
workflows' DOM - the fact which became evident during unwinding the
modal stack. The patch contains the fix for the 'Jobs' panel as well
as for other copy-pasted snippets of workflow-handling code.

Change-Id: Id2544c18c27ae3432e6fa43f19cd1459ffb34871
Closes-Bug: #1414586

commit_message:
Bump alembic to 0.7.2

Alembic 0.7.2 fixes a significant bug in 0.7.1 with handling
deduplication of unique indexes and unique constraints.

https://bitbucket.org/zzzeek/alembic/issue/251/

This bug fix is necessary for Nova to start utilizing existing
functionality in oslo.db that compares the results of the migrations
with the model.

Change-Id: I63fb3ad22746ed8c9c2197d8216e4642396c8019

commit_message:
Switch to using oslo_* instead of oslo.*

The oslo team is recommending everyone to switch to the
non-namespaced versions of libraries. Updating the hacking
rule to include a check to prevent oslo.* import from
creeping back in.
oslo.messaging is the only exception because this package doesn't
currently support non-namespaced imports.

Change-Id: I3987e651bc880c8ffa7c0105df0298679dcd3a43

commit_message:
Support qemu as virt_type

KVM currently is the default hypervisor to apply all compute nodes,
however kvm cannot work on virtual machine. So the fix will automatically
switch to qemu from kvm when it runs on top of a vm and
openstack.compute.libvirt.virt_auto is true.

Change-Id: I7ff87f7d9e77c1434eb2f39e4c43f208aa90d43a
Closes-Bug: #1334913

[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-01-26 22:23:51.000000000', 'files': ['oslosphinx/__init__.py'], 'message': 'Allow alternate OpenStack themes

By default oslosphinx forces projects that use it to use the theme
contained in the package. The documentation team wants to provide a
separate theme for some parts of the docs.openstack.org site. They are
going to distribute it in their own package, but do still want to be
able to use other features of oslosphinx. This change allows any name
that starts "openstack" to be used, while retaining the default behavior
of inserting the "openstack" theme if a project is using a different
default or has not set a theme.

Change-Id: I7a2c5a5c3805685b8fa0baaa47393d5fec312f30
'}]
commit_message:
Allow alternate OpenStack themes

By default oslosphinx forces projects that use it to use the theme
contained in the package. The documentation team wants to provide a
separate theme for some parts of the docs.openstack.org site. They are
going to distribute it in their own package, but do still want to be
able to use other features of oslosphinx. This change allows any name
that starts "openstack" to be used, while retaining the default behavior
of inserting the "openstack" theme if a project is using a different
default or has not set a theme.

Change-Id: I7a2c5a5c3805685b8fa0baaa47393d5fec312f30

We use a method of combining 2 timeseries rather than iterating and
deleting values, as it's 2 times faster to do so.

commit_message:
Add dispersion command to swift-ring-builder

Output a dispersion report that shows how many parts have each replica count
at each tier along with some additional context.  Also the max_dispersion is a
good canary for what a reasonable overload might be.

Also display a warning on rebalance if the ring's dispersion is sub-optimal.

The primitive form of the dispersion graph is cached on the builder, but the
dispersion command will build it on the fly if you have a ring that was last
rebalanced before the change.

Also add --force option to rebalance to make it write a ring even if less than
1% of parts moved.

Try to clarify some dispersion and balance a little bit in the ring section of
the architectural overview.

Co-Authored-By: Christian Schwede <christian.schwede@enovance.com>
Co-Authored-By: Darrell Bishop <darrell@swiftstack.com>

Change-Id: I7696df25d092fac56588080722e0a4167ed2c824

commit_message:
Fix filter_query in drac/power interface

While enumerating the DCIM_ComputerSystem class, the filter wasn't set
against the same class but against CIM_ComputerSystem in the query for
get_power_state. It caused inconsistency between 11th and 12th
generation servers. In the response, 11th generation server used the
CIM_ComputerSystem namespace, while 12th generation used
DCIM_ComputerSystem. Ironic looked for DCIM_ComputerSystem in the
response, thus failing for 11th generation servers. With the patch, the
response is in the DCIM_ComputerSystem namespace regardless of the
generation of the server.

Closes-Bug: #1409036

commit_message:
Remove redundant [C|c]ritical|CRITICAL pattern

This patch removes '[C|c]ritical|CRITICAL' from the AUDITLOGLEVEL
pattern as this pattern is more completely covered by the later
'[C|c]rit?(?:ical)?|CRIT?(?:ICAL)?' pattern.

This also removes a pattern bug as 'CRITICAL' should have been
'CRITICAL|' anyway.

Closes-Bug: 1401091

subject: Refactor auth plugin loading
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2015-01-23 21:34:55.000000000', 'files': ['openstack/module_loader.py', 'openstack/tests/test_module_loader.py', 'openstack/connection.py'], 'message': "Refactor auth plugin loading

I wanted to move the auth plugin loading code out of connection
for a couple of reasons:
* I wanted to be able to get a list of auth plugins without a
  connection.
* In the future, we'll want to load service extensions which the
  module loader can handle.
* The loading of service extensions needs to happen before we
  have a connection so we can assemble user preferences for those
  services.
At some point I think the user preference class will have the
module loader and handle these things, but I think it would be
a lot to digest all those changes.

Change-Id: I3abc47a6252bfca26cc1ab2e33553fe06b7b14c2
"}]
commit_message:
Refactor auth plugin loading

I wanted to move the auth plugin loading code out of connection
for a couple of reasons:
* I wanted to be able to get a list of auth plugins without a
  connection.
* In the future, we'll want to load service extensions which the
  module loader can handle.
* The loading of service extensions needs to happen before we
  have a connection so we can assemble user preferences for those
  services.
At some point I think the user preference class will have the
module loader and handle these things, but I think it would be
a lot to digest all those changes.

Change-Id: I3abc47a6252bfca26cc1ab2e33553fe06b7b14c2

commit_message:
Cisco N1KV: Enable HTTPs communication with VSM

Right now Cisco N1KV communicates with VSM using http.
This commit will make HTTPs the default communication of the plugin
and will also enable to configure that the plugin does SSL
verification of the VSM certificate.
The verification is optional since it needs an out of band
way to put the VSM certicate in the controller.
Closes-Bug: 1365600

Change-Id: Id9eacbc208261b3917d15c2a9959317d8e2a99ac

subject: Client command extension support
revisions:
[{'number': 4, 'created': '2015-01-23 12:48:00.000000000', 'files': ['neutronclient/common/extension.py', 'test-requirements.txt', 'neutronclient/tests/unit/test_discover.py', 'neutronclient/shell.py', 'neutronclient/v2_0/contrib/__init__.py'], 'message': "Client command extension support

The extension support provided by this change is limited to shell extensions.
The library is not extended by this change. Another change to make extensions
work as library functions will be needed. If desired this change can be
expanded to include that functionality.

Extensions are installed by either placing a conforming module in the
appropriate directory (/v2.0/contrib) or by installing a package into the
environment with a name that ends with '_python_neutronclient_ext'.

A conforming module, at a minimum:
* exposes new commands through a dictionary whose key is the command and value
  is a class that subclasses an extension.ClientExtension* class
* provides classes that subclass extension.ClientExtension* classes

Provides client command extensions through a new class, NeutronClientExtension.
The precedence of command loading are as follows:
* hard coded commands are loaded first
* contribued commands (those in /contrib)
* external commands (installed in the environment) are loaded last

Commands that have the same name will be overwritten by commands that are
loaded later. To greatly change the execution of a command for your particular
extension you only need to override the execute method.

An example extension, while not included, can be seen at:
https://github.com/Cerberus98/quark_python_neutronclient_ext

Change-Id: Ie999d06e558263887dbc3e2b56320430017506c1
Implements: blueprint extensible-neutronclient
"}]
commit_message:
Client command extension support

The extension support provided by this change is limited to shell extensions.
The library is not extended by this change. Another change to make extensions
work as library functions will be needed. If desired this change can be
expanded to include that functionality.

Extensions are installed by either placing a conforming module in the
appropriate directory (/v2.0/contrib) or by installing a package into the
environment with a name that ends with '_python_neutronclient_ext'.

A conforming module, at a minimum:
* exposes new commands through a dictionary whose key is the command and value
  is a class that subclasses an extension.ClientExtension* class
* provides classes that subclass extension.ClientExtension* classes

Provides client command extensions through a new class, NeutronClientExtension.
The precedence of command loading are as follows:
* hard coded commands are loaded first
* contribued commands (those in /contrib)
* external commands (installed in the environment) are loaded last

Commands that have the same name will be overwritten by commands that are
loaded later. To greatly change the execution of a command for your particular
extension you only need to override the execute method.

An example extension, while not included, can be seen at:
https://github.com/Cerberus98/quark_python_neutronclient_ext

Change-Id: Ie999d06e558263887dbc3e2b56320430017506c1
Implements: blueprint extensible-neutronclient

commit_message:
A decorated for handling errors

Add a @handle_errors decorator, that wraps the method in a try-except
with the exceptions.handle() call in it. This lets us define consistent
error handling for a particular API call, without having to copy-paste
a lot of boilerplate code and repeating messages everywhere.

Change-Id: I47cdfac7e9beb98ccbe3aa5eeefdf81741cfbb7e
Implements: blueprint horizon-boilerplate-error-handling

commit_message:
Deleting currently scoped project breaks session

If you create a project, add your user as an admin user, and then
while still in that project context delete the project, horizon
behaves inconsistently.  Some dashboards will render, some others
will report permission errors.

This is caused by the invalidation of the current user's token.

This fix will log the current user out with a logout_reason explaining
why, and ask them to re-authenticate.

Change-Id: Id34085d3f61e60b4b1250c6a8eaa64c8f751b6c9
Closes-Bug: #1324662

commit_message:
Horizon new launch instance form

    A new launch instance form in a pure angular development
    Here are the enhancement:
        - better use of less and bootstrap
(part of https://blueprints.launchpad.net/horizon/+spec/css-breakdown)
        - use of a centralized list of variable.
It makes css customization easier, improve maintainability and reduce
code footprint. (part of
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/horizon/+spec/centralized-color-palette)
        - use of angular for all the heavy lift client side (part of
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/horizon/+spec/horizon-angular)
        - reduce the use of class based view put the displaying logic
on client side and only handle datas on server side.

    TODO list:
        - provide some tests for the client side
        - split this commit in one for each blueprint

Implements: blueprint launch-instance-ux-enhancement

Change-Id: Ie0d5b33c0919c7378eae30ad51dcd2f8d297861a

commit_message:
Catch connection refused in API request

Instead of using exceptions.check_message in order to determine if a
message from an API request, always catch requests.ConnectionError and
set _safe_message there.

commit_message:
Allow admin to set instance defaults per image

This adds all of the initial code for setting instance default
values on an image, including the table action and resulting panel.
The Launch Instance workflow is updated to handle these defaults.
This also adds support for the first instance default which is
the flavor.

The Instance Defaults panel can be accessed from the admin images
table. Each field will allow setting a default value and whether or
not the value can be changed from this default. If not, then the
field will not be displayed.

Change-Id: I1fcb603230af6a9e2c23807b3792b6bf9c2bd4ff
Partially Implements: blueprint instance-defaults-per-image

revisions:
[{'number': 11, 'created': '2014-02-24 18:49:54.000000000', 'files': ['openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/flavors/tables.py', 'horizon/middleware.py', 'horizon/static/horizon/js/horizon.modals.js'], 'message': 'Fixes modal_stack

Currently, the View Flavor Extra Specs modal is shown as an embedded
modal within a full page. This patchset enables the modal to be rendered as a
full modal.

The solution is in several parts:

1. Initiation of "View Flavor Extra Specs" modal

This only requires the addition of the "ajax-modal" class to the appropriate
LinkAction. This ensurese the view as launched as a modal.

2. Fix to submit handling

This is where the bulk of the fix resides (horizon.modals.js). The basic
idea is that on submit, we check to see if there are any other modals on the
modal_stack. If so, we reload the top modal on the stack. This forces the
modal to reload its data (via ajax) from the server. This is significantly
faster than doing a full page redraw, and also much cleaner from a user
experience perspective (although the redraw is not ideal, it would be better
to dynamically reload the table -- but that is a much more significant
undertaking). The bulk of the code is in factoring the existing modal
launch code into a new method "horizon.modals.launch" to enable its re-use.

If there are no remaining modals on the stack, we simply redirect to the
success url.

3. Fix message display

Currently, success messages for a modal are only displayed on the next full
view render. This behavior is implemented in horizon.middleware. A mechanism
already exists for feeding these messages back to the client via the
X-Horizon-Messages response header. By using this method, messages can be
displayed while a modal is active.

Change-Id: I69fadb7436fcce679912abb39227ca34e1f6eded
Closes-Bug: #1276735
'}]
commit_message:
Fixes modal_stack

Currently, the View Flavor Extra Specs modal is shown as an embedded
modal within a full page. This patchset enables the modal to be rendered as a
full modal.

The solution is in several parts:

1. Initiation of "View Flavor Extra Specs" modal

This only requires the addition of the "ajax-modal" class to the appropriate
LinkAction. This ensurese the view as launched as a modal.

2. Fix to submit handling

This is where the bulk of the fix resides (horizon.modals.js). The basic
idea is that on submit, we check to see if there are any other modals on the
modal_stack. If so, we reload the top modal on the stack. This forces the
modal to reload its data (via ajax) from the server. This is significantly
faster than doing a full page redraw, and also much cleaner from a user
experience perspective (although the redraw is not ideal, it would be better
to dynamically reload the table -- but that is a much more significant
undertaking). The bulk of the code is in factoring the existing modal
launch code into a new method "horizon.modals.launch" to enable its re-use.

If there are no remaining modals on the stack, we simply redirect to the
success url.

3. Fix message display

Currently, success messages for a modal are only displayed on the next full
view render. This behavior is implemented in horizon.middleware. A mechanism
already exists for feeding these messages back to the client via the
X-Horizon-Messages response header. By using this method, messages can be
displayed while a modal is active.

Change-Id: I69fadb7436fcce679912abb39227ca34e1f6eded
Closes-Bug: #1276735

commit_message:
Edit use heading property for page validation

*Every page has heading. This heading can be used for page validation in
 the same manner as _page_title.

*Make page validation implicit. Heading and page title must be specified
 before calling BasePage constructor.

*_heading and _page_title must be specified through overriding the
 _set_page_validation_data method and setting page_title and heading
 variables

*Move is_the_current_page method to BasePage as there is no use for it
 in Pageobject class, login page has to have its own is_the_current_page
 method because of its special behaviour.

*The LoginPage validation was refactor and test must have been
 adequately edited as well.

Partially implements blueprint: selenium-integration-testing

Change-Id: I584e94ff8bc6fc6abadebf65c788b5262e78ea33

commit_message:
Combined host aggregate editing forms

Added in workflow step to update host aggregate info. Renamed
host aggregate workflow to better reflect its new functionality.
Deleted old form and template files that are no longer used.
Updated unit tests to be compatible with new attributes and calls
being made. Updated urls and constants to reflect new changes.

commit_message:
Adds client side validation for image creation

Client side validation for required fields were added in the
admin and project forms for creating Images. Also if validation
fails on server side, the tmp file is also removed. This patch
is based on the solution provided by Maxime Vidori

Closes-Bug: #1253791

commit_message:
Use original context rather than returned value of contribute()

Workflow.__init__ and finalize now uses a return value of contribute
as self.context. However each contribute() method updates context
object incrementally and there is no need to use a return value.
By not using a returned context, we can avoid an programming error
(like bug 1303091) to reset self.context to None.

According to the above observation, this commit changes Workflow
__init__ and finalize not to use return value of contribute()
and update contribute() methods in dashboard implementation.

Change-Id: I70fd35fde66e6dc90281237eb7a0f251809b92ed
Closes-Bug: #1303091

commit_message:
Fixing the health monitor's association bugs

- When trying to disassociate a health monitor from pool, the
modal does not show the currently associated monitors.
The list was empty before this fix.
- When trying to associate a new monitor, all available monitors
were shown including the already associated ones.
- The pool details tab was showing all available monitors when
there were no associated monitors.
- Unit test data update.

Change-Id: I6953addd9d1f7d8c9f3218247d4b0a6ea69d548a
Closes-Bug: #1328923
Closes-Bug: #1328931
Closes-Bug: #1328928
Co-Authored-By: Andres Buraschi <andres.buraschi@intel.com>

commit_message:
Proof of concept for push-based communication

This uses SockJS to update instance state listed in
/projects/instances/.

The server hooks into the OpenStack RPC notifications so we need to be
able to configure the RPC backend, etc.

Start the server with:

    ./horizon-realtime.py --config-file etc/horizon/horizon-realtime.conf

To try it out, navigate to http://localhost:8080, log in and go to the
Project -> Instances page. Then launch an instance using the Nova
command line client and try to suspend, resume and delete it from there.

The UI should update automatically.

Implements blueprint realtime-communication

Change-Id: I2fb1c479c2dd3c6bb7b24564df0a598ff57e09ac
Signed-off-by: Tomas Sedovic <tsedovic@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Add support for disabling regions

If there are multiple regions specified in keystone you might only want to show a single one in the dashboard.
This add the option to only show region x.
By default it will show all regions, when ALLOWED_REGION is set it will show the region set there

Closes-Bug: 1356738
Change-Id: I4b3e9742599b17ef2c4bbd7687e106a2bd94cdd1

commit_message:
Per Project-User Quotas Support

Currently nova supports per-project-user quotas. The purpose of this is
to implement the interactions with nova to support quota per project-
user management from Horizon.

Changes:
- new form for managing quotas for user
- nova api updated to handle user_id when getting and updating quota
- usage quota updated handle user_id when getting and updating quota
- unit tests

implements: blueprint per-user-quotas

Co-Authored-By: Sergio Cazzolato <sergio.j.cazzolato@intel.com>

Change-Id: I117ae7639a85ef7216fd8fd47a9da87767670af6

Per Lin-Hua Cheng's comment:

This patchset implements this behavior for AddMembers and RemoveMembers

Closes-Bug: #1276217

commit_message:
Horizon errors out when adding myself to a group

Per Lin-Hua Cheng's comment:

    Keystone revokes the token of the user added to the group.
    If the logon user was added, redirect the user to logout.

This patchset implements this behavior for AddMembers and RemoveMembers
actions of the GroupMembers and GroupNonMembers Tables in
dashboards.admin.groups.

Change-Id: I98c2ab804fb29a10aa199616854d10fea976055b
Closes-Bug: #1276217

commit_message:
And check for flavor extras cpu_period

Flavor extras cpu_period has a range [1000, 1000000].
Now there is no check about the value.

And then if you create an instance using this flavor,
it will get a exception: unsupported configuration:
Value of cputune period must be in range [1000, 1000000]

Closes-Bug: #1327061

commit_message:
Support for cisco DFA in horizon

To support cisco Dynamic Fabric Automation (DFA) requirement,
a new option should be displayed when a network is created.
The new option is called 'configuration profile'. In order to conditionally
execute the changes for cisco DFA, a new flag will be added to
OPENSTACK_NEUTRON_NETWORK, i.e. 'cisco-dfa'.
If the flag is True, the 'configuration profile' will be displayed along with
other options when creating a network and user can select one of the available
profile from a list. The list of profiles are fetched from the newly added
database. The database is getting populated by a driver which will be added as
part of ML2 cisco DFA mechanism driver.

The link below has detail information regarding cisco DFA:
www.cisco.com/go/dfa

Implements: blueprint horizon-cisco-dfa-support

Change-Id: I1e5694971faf09ab96ed25b5044e40765720b43b

commit_message:
Fixes Swift object url encoding issue when name has spaces

* Removes quoting the container and object name before
  sending the request to Django. Django url resolve does the
  url encoding starting version 1.6.

Change-Id: Idbf6bcb22c28c51be59ea950e428382482f7bc76
Closes-Bug: #1336603

commit_message:
Add translation layer from django

Added translation layer allows to test different language mutations
without breaking code when explicitly specifying string related to the
current language mutation.To change language do:
import django.utils.translation as tr
tr.activate('de')  # this will change language to German

Locale files are gathered from openstack_dashboard/locale and
horizon/locale, those locales must by compiled first, therefore i
add message compilation before the execution of integration tests.

This patch does not manipulate with horizon language setting, it only
uses django translation module for obtaining string translations.

Every new patch should use the ugettext function as described in
loginpage.py, projectpage.py ...

Simple change language test was added.

Partially implements blueprint: selenium-integration-testing

Change-Id: If43bb29a5dec75caa6ad42d484654182a99bd62d

commit_message:
For Trove panels, stop requiring Swift in catalog

* Provide flag (TROVE_BACKUPS) with 3 choices: on, off, or consult
  catalog.
    * If value is True, backup-related panels are shown.
    * If value is False, backup-related panels are hidden.
    * If value is 'catalog', consult catalog (legacy behavior).
* Moves download backup to Actions column instead of dedicated column.
* Stop using containers panel for downloading backups (which checks
  'openstack.services.object-store' permission and additionally uses
  Swift from catalog); instead use swiftclient directly built from
  backup's locationRef

Closes-Bug: #1276814
Change-Id: Ie6e04c4e44090db082ce14e0cd8a178ab0d3c214

commit_message:
angularJS workflow for launching heat stacks

  - replaces django multi-step form view with angular wizard
  - allows for multiple file uploads, client side file downloads
    etc. Fixes issues with file locations & environment files
  - removes support for URL template files
  - requires a custom heatclient from here:
      o https://github.com/jsomara/python-heatclient/tree/envfiles
    if this becomes a blocking issue, we can add that method to horizon
    temporarily. The other possibility is that it is extended to support
    nested stacks as well (a Juno goal). This patch includes this code
    inside horizon, with the intention of removing it when support becomes
    available in upstream python-heatclient
  - there are outstanding messaging improvements (error messages, etc) that
    this patch could take advantage of for better message dialogs

To test this, check out sample environment & template files here. You'll
notice that the referenced file in the environment will get added in
stage2 of the wizard. If you don't have any file references to resolve,
it will go straight to stage3.
- https://github.com/hardys/demo_templates/blob/master/juno_summit_intro_to_heat/example2_server_with_volume_nested/server_with_volume.yaml
- https://github.com/hardys/demo_templates/blob/master/juno_summit_intro_to_heat/example4_provider_environment/env_server_with_volume.yaml
- https://github.com/hardys/demo_templates/blob/master/juno_summit_intro_to_heat/example4_provider_environment/server_with_volume_env.yaml

Closes-Bug: #1322258
Partial-Implements:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/horizon/+spec/heat-nested-stack
Change-Id: I99b21d4b73375229a2abca346342bfe948098e5f

commit_message:
Support of multiple plural forms in BatchActions

Horizon only supports singular and one plural form, when there are
languages as Polish and Russian that have more than one plural
form.
Then, this patch creates the function get_data_type_display_name in
BatchAction and its inherited classes to let translators to
manage multiple plural forms.

Change-Id: Ie63552034878b4ae59ff4b7853955341e5fb30e0
Closes-Bug:#1253174

commit_message:
Extending quota support for neutron LBaaS entities

Extending quota mechanism to support neutron
LBaaS entities. Adding quota for vips, pools, members
and health monitors.

Added new function to check if LBaaS extension is supported,
using the new function for disabling LBaaS quotas.

Changed the quota retrieving function (usage.quotas.get_tenant_quota_data)
to get all neutron quotas and not only the floating ip.

Added new unit tests for testing neutron quotas retrieval
for cases when neutron quotas/security_groups/lbaas extensions
are enabled/disabled

This is one of four changes related to the BP.
This one is for horizon/openstack-dashboard project.
Another one is for neutron project,
another one for python-neutronclient
and another one for tempest project.

See blueprint neutron-quota-extension for another three changes.
See horizon bug opened for following the BP: bug #1284107

Change-Id: I74e5b6c0451538aa6721a8ed1acbea673ac533b3
Implements: blueprint neutron-quota-extension

Both cinderclient and troveclient don't raise an error when they fail to
connect -- they just emit a warning. That means, that when someone

commit_message:
Error on log error messages

Both cinderclient and troveclient don't raise an error when they fail to
connect -- they just emit a warning. That means, that when someone
forgets to mock the calls for them in the tests, the tests still pass,
but spam a lot of messages to the console. This patch makes the tests
fail in such a situation, by defining a logging handler that raises an
exception.

Change-Id: Ib098b0d33cdb047934018acc9819bc841e0b4689
Closes-bug: #1335082

commit_message:
Exclude snapshots from images at instance launch

While creating the instance, instance snapshots appear in two
lists: 'boot from image' and 'boot from snapshot'. This fix is
to address that.

Change-Id: I6acddebe566b92128a3d338909ddb9d2375b675f
Closes-Bug: 1296627

commit_message:
Add domain select to admin network create form

This adds a domain select to the Admin -> Create Network form
if there are multiple enabled domains that contain enabled
projects. The domain select will narrow down the list of projects
that can be selected. In this scenario the list of projects are
also grouped by domain.

Closes-Bug: 1340873

subject: Change default session backend to cached_db
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2014-11-06 14:28:28.000000000', 'files': ['openstack_dashboard/settings.py'], 'message': 'Change default session backend to cached_db

Horizon needs more space to handle session data. With the Identity
API moving towards V3 (that has a significantly enlarged token),
we need to work with sessions beyond 4KB.
Between the types of session backend offered by Django, we decided
to opt by the cached_db option. Possible benefits include:
* Unlimited session size
* Reduced traffic between client-server (smaller cookies)
* DB is more persistent and reliable than Memcache
* SQLite is embedded with Python

Change-Id: I585ff29ceef8d52e5baf3be1b6040572488897e1
Closes-bug: 1382079
'}]
commit_message:
Change default session backend to cached_db

Horizon needs more space to handle session data. With the Identity
API moving towards V3 (that has a significantly enlarged token),
we need to work with sessions beyond 4KB.
Between the types of session backend offered by Django, we decided
to opt by the cached_db option. Possible benefits include:
* Unlimited session size
* Reduced traffic between client-server (smaller cookies)
* DB is more persistent and reliable than Memcache
* SQLite is embedded with Python

Change-Id: I585ff29ceef8d52e5baf3be1b6040572488897e1
Closes-bug: 1382079

commit_message:
Replace horizon alerting with an angular one

    Horizon alerting is now fully integrated into the angular
application. The object horizon.msg is available in the application
in order to keep the compatibility, it is a link to the new angular
service object.

Change-Id: I95c8b9b38843db9ecbc625b02fcd696b6981bd7b
Implements: blueprint horizon-angular

commit_message:
Partial fix missing keyboard focus from Console's iframe

The iframe in Instance Console doesn't get focus on loading, so the user
cannot type into the console, this change is focusing the iframe on
hovering mouse over it.

Partial-Bug: #1389117
Change-Id: I39fb5a26645d3805070a875386ec91b8048b8c79

commit_message:
Make table columns configurable

Add the possibility to configure visible table columns, by adding
an action button to the list of table's actions. Clicking on this button
opens a modal form dialog which makes it possible to choose the
table columns to display. The choice of columns is then saved to the
session as well as to a cookie.

When the table is rendered, the selected columns configuration is
retrieved from session or from the cookie if nothing is found in the
session. Taking into account this configuration, the table is then
rendered, displaying only the selected columns. If no configuration
is found in either session or the cookie, all columns are displayed.

To illustrate this newly added capability, the columns selection has
been enabled for the tables on the Host Aggregates panel on Admin
dashboard. The ability to select columns will be added to the rest of
the tables in a following patch.

Partially implements blueprint: configure-table-columns
Change-Id: Ida4fb0f959c8f80e5c5befc235df50834a183d95

commit_message:
Natural sort the instance name in all tables and tabs

In a few cases, the data to be sorted was a list of dicts or a list of
strings instead of a list of objects.  Previously, natural_sort() only
accepted an attribute name, so in order to make it more flexible to
handle this scenario it now accepts as its single optional argument a
getter function.

Closes-Bug: #1329954
Change-Id: Ie49e6f6f746764585ff711400f7a9c63a76c4a25

commit_message:
Network Tab does not show external network column

Modified the network tab to have new column
'External Network' in admin dashboard and
project dashboard by modifying the NetworksTable
class in tables.py

It is confusing to just have only shared column
and not external network yes/no

Modified the column name to 'External' as per review comments

Closes-bug: #1350237
Change-Id: Id5c4783de9f80ab6bf4fc50270ac7f1711f1cbfa

commit_message:
Allow filtering on instance status using translated values

This allows for a tuple of filter values to be used for selecting
a filter value for any given filter field in a table. This way the
selected filter value can be translated while the actual filter
value used is a known constant. This is implemented for the Status
filter on the instances tables.

Change-Id: I48845c25c49b30b8dfdb27ff12f29779d0dade32
Closes-Bug: #1365754

Mark host down for maintenance

Implement host maintenance in the hypervisors panel.
On each compute host a maintenance button was added.
This button enable/disable the compute host for future
maintenance.

commit_message:
Separate jasmine tests between services and controllers

    The separation allow to correctly test services in a dedicated jasmine
environment and test controllers without taking care of which dependency needs
to be loaded.

subject: A project shouldn't be deleted when there are instances running
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2014-08-18 10:13:30.000000000', 'files': ['openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/projects/tables.py', 'openstack_dashboard/api/keystone.py'], 'message': 'A project shouldn't be deleted when there are instances running

Initially the admin user was able to delete a tenant even if
it had instances associated with it. This fix will throw the
error ("Failed to delete tenant <tenant_id>. There are instances
associated with it. Please delete the instances and try again."),
if a tenant has instances associated with it. The tenant will
only get deleted if no instance(s) is associated with it.

Change-Id: Ia6fd76b99454516e4a8966b58a9262962c9b3ec0
Closes-Bug: #1288230
'}]
commit_message:
A project shouldn't be deleted when there are instances running

Initially the admin user was able to delete a tenant even if
it had instances associated with it. This fix will throw the
error ("Failed to delete tenant <tenant_id>. There are instances
associated with it. Please delete the instances and try again."),
if a tenant has instances associated with it. The tenant will
only get deleted if no instance(s) is associated with it.

Change-Id: Ia6fd76b99454516e4a8966b58a9262962c9b3ec0
Closes-Bug: #1288230

commit_message:
Show focus on left side navigation

This bug is an accessibility problem. Navigation focus is not visible
when using Tab-key to navigate.

This fix make focus clearly visible due to use contrast color.

Change-Id: I26072a1745f675bd418d6fd3b8920ab25ecedb15
Closes-Bug: 1315488

commit_message:
Clarify image creation comment about compressed image support

The previous comment about tar.gz support was misleading,
as tar.gz is not actually supported. The only thing that is
supported is uploading .gz'ed files as far as I can say.

Change-Id: Ifab9fc64c46998f3c924df445d804b91a8cef171
